---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Color-Magnitude Diagram - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Color-Magnitude Diagram</h1>
        
        <div class="infobox">
            <h3 class="infobox-title">Color-Magnitude Diagram (CMD)</h3>
            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Type:</th>
                    <td>Diagnostic diagram</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Axes:</th>
                    <td>Color (y) vs Magnitude (x)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Common colors:</th>
                    <td>g-r, u-r, U-V, NUV-r</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Key features:</th>
                    <td><WikiLink slug="pages/Red_Sequence" text="Red Sequence" /><br>
                        <WikiLink slug="pages/Blue_Cloud" text="Blue Cloud" /><br>
                        <WikiLink slug="pages/Green_Valley" text="Green Valley" /></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>First used:</th>
                    <td>Early 20th century (stars)<br>
                        1970s (galaxies)</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </div>

        <p>The <strong>color-magnitude diagram (CMD)</strong> is a fundamental tool in astronomy that plots the color of objects against their brightness. For galaxies, it reveals the <WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Bimodality" text="bimodal distribution" /> of the galaxy population and serves as a key diagnostic for understanding <WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Evolution" text="galaxy evolution" />.</p>

        <h2 id="section-0">Construction</h2>
        
        <p>A galaxy CMD typically plots:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>X-axis</strong>: Absolute magnitude (often M<sub>r</sub> or M<sub>*</sub>), with brighter galaxies to the right</li>
            <li><strong>Y-axis</strong>: Color index (e.g., g-r, u-r), with redder galaxies toward the top</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Common color indices include:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>g-r</strong>: Optical color sensitive to recent star formation</li>
            <li><strong>u-r</strong>: Broader baseline, more sensitive to stellar population age</li>
            <li><strong>NUV-r</strong>: Very sensitive to recent star formation</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-1">Major Features</h2>

        <h3><WikiLink slug="pages/Red_Sequence" text="Red Sequence" /></h3>
        <p>A tight correlation of red galaxies showing:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Little ongoing star formation</li>
            <li>Dominated by old stellar populations</li>
            <li>Color-magnitude relation: brighter galaxies are slightly redder</li>
            <li>Small intrinsic scatter (~0.05 mag in color)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3><WikiLink slug="pages/Blue_Cloud" text="Blue Cloud" /></h3>
        <p>A more diffuse population of blue galaxies:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Active star formation</li>
            <li>Younger stellar populations</li>
            <li>Larger scatter in color at fixed magnitude</li>
            <li>Weaker color-magnitude relation</li>
        </ul>

        <h3><WikiLink slug="pages/Green_Valley" text="Green Valley" /></h3>
        <p>The sparsely populated region between the two main populations:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Transition region for <WikiLink slug="pages/Quenching" text="quenching" /> galaxies</li>
            <li>May contain <WikiLink slug="pages/Dusty_Star-Forming_Galaxies" text="dusty star-forming galaxies" /></li>
            <li>Population depends on color choice and dust correction</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-2">Physical Interpretation</h2>

        <p>Galaxy colors primarily reflect:</p>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Stellar population age</strong>: Older populations are redder</li>
            <li><strong>Star formation history</strong>: Recent star formation produces blue light</li>
            <li><strong>Metallicity</strong>: Metal-rich populations are slightly redder</li>
            <li><strong>Dust extinction</strong>: Dust reddens galaxy colors</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="section-3">Evolution with Redshift</h2>

        <p>The CMD evolves significantly with cosmic time:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>The red sequence builds up over time (<WikiLink slug="pages/Red_Sequence_Formation" text="red sequence formation" />)</li>
            <li>The blue cloud was more prominent at higher redshift</li>
            <li>The transition mass between populations decreases with time</li>
            <li>Colors of both populations were bluer in the past</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-4">Applications</h2>

        <ol>
            <li><strong>Galaxy Classification</strong>: Separating star-forming from quiescent galaxies</li>
            <li><strong>Evolutionary Studies</strong>: Tracking galaxy transformation</li>
            <li><strong>Environmental Effects</strong>: Comparing field vs cluster populations</li>
            <li><strong>Photometric Redshifts</strong>: The red sequence as a redshift indicator</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="section-5">Caveats and Complications</h2>

        <ul>
            <li><strong>Dust effects</strong>: Can move blue galaxies into the green valley</li>
            <li><strong>Aperture effects</strong>: Colors depend on measurement aperture</li>
            <li><strong>K-corrections</strong>: Important for high-redshift studies</li>
            <li><strong>Selection effects</strong>: Different surveys probe different populations</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-6">Related Diagrams</h2>

        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/UVJ_Diagram" text="UVJ Diagram" /> - Better separation of dusty star-forming galaxies</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Mass-Color_Diagram" text="Mass-Color Diagram" /> - Using stellar mass instead of luminosity</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/SFR-Mass_Diagram" text="SFR-Mass Diagram" /> - The star-forming main sequence</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-7">Historical Development</h2>

        <p>The CMD concept originated with stellar astronomy (<WikiLink slug="pages/Hertzsprung-Russell_Diagram" text="Hertzsprung-Russell diagram" />) and was adapted for galaxies as large surveys became available:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>1970s: First galaxy CMDs from photographic surveys</li>
            <li>2000s: <WikiLink slug="pages/SDSS" text="SDSS" /> revealed clear bimodality</li>
            <li>2010s: Deep surveys extended to high redshift</li>
            <li>2020s: <WikiLink slug="pages/LSST" text="LSST" /> will provide unprecedented statistics</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-8">See Also</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Colors" text="Galaxy Colors" /> - Physical origin of galaxy colors</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Stellar_Populations" text="Stellar Populations" /> - What determines integrated light</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Selection" text="Galaxy Selection" /> - How CMDs define samples</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="page-tags">
            <strong>Tags:</strong>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Fundamental_Tools" text="Fundamental Tools" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Observations" text="Observations" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Galaxy_Properties" text="Galaxy Properties" />
        </div>
  </main>
</Base>
